(1, 'Practice 1', 2, 6, '<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><b><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">LOCKED DOORS, OPEN ACCESS</span></b></span></span></p>\n\n<p style=\"margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\">&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">The word, &ldquo;security&rdquo;, has both positive and negative connotations. Most of us would say that we crave security for all its positive virtues, both physical and psychological- its evocation of the safety of home, of undying love, or of freedom from need. More negatively, the word nowadays conjures up images of that huge industry which has developed to protect individuals and property from invasion by &ldquo; outsiders&rdquo;, ostensibly malicious and intent on theft or willful damage.</span></span></span></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">Increasingly, because they are situated in urban areas of escalating crime, those buildings which used to allow free access to employees and other users (buildings such as offices, schools, colleges or hospitals) now do not. Entry areas which in another age were called &ldquo;Reception&rdquo; are now manned by security staff. Receptionists, whose task it was to receive visitors and to make them welcome before passing them on to the person that had come to see, have been replaced by those whose task it is to bar entry to the unauthorized, the unwanted or the plain unappealing.</span></span></span></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">Inside, these buildings are divided into &ldquo;secure zones&rdquo; which often have all the trappings of combination locks and burglar alarm. These devices bar entry to the uninitiated, hinder circulation, and create parameters of time and space for user access. Within the spaces created by these zones, individual rooms are themselves under lock and key, which is a particular problem when it means that working space becomes compartmentalized.</span></span></span></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">To combat the consequent difficulty of access to people at a physical level, we have now developed technological access. Computers sit on every desk and are linked to one another, and in many cases to an external universe of other computer, so that messages can be passed to and fro. Here too, security plays a part, since we must not be allowed access to messages destined for others. And so the password was invented. Now correspondence between individuals goes from desk and cannot be accessed by colleagues. Library catalogues can be searched from one&rsquo;s desk. Papers can be delivered to, and received from, other people at the press of a button.</span></span></span></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">And yet it seems that, just as work is isolating individuals more and more, organizations are recogning the advantages of &ldquo;team-work&rdquo;, perhaps in order to encourage employees to talk to one another again. Yet, how can groups work in teams if the possibilities for communication are reduced? How can they work together if e-mail provides a convenient electronic shield behind which the blurring of public and private can be exploited by the less scrupulous? If voice-mail walls up messages behind a password? If I can&rsquo;t leave a message on my colleague&rsquo;s desk because hiss office is locked?</span></span></span></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">Team-work conceals the fact that another kind of security, &ldquo;job security&rdquo;, is almost always not on offer. Just as organizations now recognize three kinds of physical resources: those they buy, those they lease long-term and those they rent short-term-so it is with their human resources, Some employees have permanent contracts, some have short-term contacts, and some are regarded simply as casual labour.</span></span></span></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">Telecommunication systems offer us the direct line, which means that individuals can be contacted without the caller having to talk to anyone else. Voice-mail and the answer phone mean that individuals can communicate without ever actually talking to one an other. If we are unfortunate enough to contact an organization with a sophisticated touch-tone dialing system, we can buy things and pay for them without ever speaking to a human being.</span></span></span></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:justify; margin:0in 0in 0.0001pt\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:13.0pt\">To combat this closing in on ourselves we have the Internet, which opens out communication channels more widely than anyone could possibly want or need. An individual&rsquo;s electronic presence on the Internet is known as the &ldquo;Home page&rdquo;- suggesting the safety and security of an electronic hearth. An elaborate system of 3-dimensional graphics distinguishes this 